[For background on oyster herpesvirus (OsHV-1, micro-var) see commentary in ProMED-mail post 20131030.2030679.

The Pacific oyster is the most important species of oyster cultivated in the United Kingdom both in terms of volume and value, with an annual production of over 1100 tonnes (metric tons). Production greatly exceeds that of the native oyster _Ostrea edulis_. Oyster herpesvirus has devastated Pacific oyster production in France, Jersey and parts of Ireland, and it is important that the disease is contained to prevent its spread to other oyster growing areas in Great Britain (http://www.defra.gov.uk/aahm/files/QA-oyster-herpesvirus-2013.pdf).

In 2010 Great Britain experienced the 1st outbreak of oyster herpesvirus at a shellfish farm in Whitstable, Kent. This outbreak was contained through the application of statutory movement controls on the affected site (http://www.defra.gov.uk/aahm/files/OHV-CD.pdf).

In 2012 there was another outbreak of oyster herpesvirus in the Blackwater Estuary, Essex (http://www.defra.gov.uk/aahm/files/CD04-2012-Confirmed-Designation-Map-Schedule.pdf).

For additional information, please refer to the Aquatic Animal Health and Movements (AAHM) website's section on "Disease designations" -- oyster herpesvirus confirmed, at http://www.defra.gov.uk/aahm/disease/oyster/. - Mod.CRD

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1fj0.]
